	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1139373">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1139373">
                  
                  I posted the following in the wizard boards on the eqplayers site and also PM'd it to Prathun.  <br />
<br />
Input appreciated.<br />
<br />
<b><u>Fixing the Wizard Spells: A Proposal for Positive Change </u></b><br />
(Warning:  This is long.)<br />
<br />
The key problems with the nerfing of the instant cast spells were:<br />
1. The nerf was based primarily on penalizing wizards for relying on those spells rather than rewarding wizards for using other spells. The small boost to EC did not improve its utility due to its poor resist mods.<br />
2. The alternative spells remained significantly disadvantageous to use due to poor dps, poor resist rates, and/or poor mana efficiency.<br />
<br />
My proposal is that wizards be encouraged to diversify their spell usage by giving them positive reinforcement for using a variety of spells. There are two steps to this process: improving existing spell lines and implementing new more strategic and complex spells into the next expansion.  This post will deal only with the first step of improving current spells.<br />
<br />
I am not talking about minor tweaks but rather some pretty major changes to a large number of the 71-75 spells, but I think we get a much better toolbox of spells to deploy and maintain our current peak dps levels while gaining some reliability and durability of dps.  I am going to base the desired dps level on roughly our current dps level with a small improvement in the reliability and durability of that dps so that these changes will not create a problem with excess dps in xp group scenarios but helps improve wizard dps on raids where mobs live longer and are more resistant. I'll go through these spell-by-spell for the proposed changes. I am going to skip a few spells that either aren't worth the attention or require much more lengthy conversation (as this is already outrageously long).<br />
<br />
1. Ethereal Conflagration. The primary problem here is the high rate of resists for this spell. If we can just improve its resist rate then honestly it starts to improve significantly. This spell is a huge investment of both time and mana, so it ought to be very reliable if we want wizards to use it. The best way is probably to change it to resist check of Fire-100. The other option is Chromatic-10, but this forces wizards to find another type of focus for this one spell, which I think is unwise if we want to encourage its use. This one change alone would boost this spell dramatically in its utility.<br />
<br />
2. Claw of Selay. This spell is wonderfully efficient but incredibly low dps due to its abnormally long cast time for such a low damage spell. The -50 resist base is ok for a low-investment spell (low mana cost, low time cast), but the 5 second cast time for really low damage makes this spell very difficult to justify using in almost any situation. Being forced to use this for mana-conservation purposes puts wizards dps not just a bit lower but right through the floor. The best solution here is simply to cut its cast time to 3 seconds and increase the damage by 25%. It will still be far less dps than EC or the instants, but at least the dps would be ok and it would become a real viable spell for long-duration fights where we need high efficiency.<br />
<br />
3. Intertwining Energy. This spell is actually not bad except that it has a terrible resist check (mr-10). In addition to MR being the worst resist base to play on, the -10 check makes this very common to resist and its casting time is too long to be playing with high resist rates. At absolute bare minimum this spell needs to be changed to MR-50, but to really make it attractive lower the cast time to four seconds and lower the damage to 2800. That will make it acceptable dps, minimally reliable, and fun to play with for the 25% chance at the spell boost buff.<br />
<br />
4. Sothgar's Flame. Mediocre efficiency, poor resists, mediocre dps = who mems this thing? First, drop the cast time to 6 seconds so we can use it. 8 seconds is far too long for anything other than a fat and hugely reliable bomb (like EC would be if it had a decent resist check). Second, change the resist mod to -100 so it becomes reliable enough to become situationally attractive. It still won't be a great spell but it would be very good in those situations where we need a little extra resist mod. It would have mediocre efficiency and at 6 second cast time would be mediocre dps, but the -100 resist mod might be enough to draw us to it.<br />
<br />
5. Chaos Immolation. I actually like this spell but I think it just needs a 25% boost to damage. Otherwise, it's fine as is. Mediocre resist mod, good casting time, acceptable average efficiency. Average dps needs some work, though, and with variable dmg spells the top end needs to be hefty. Either increase the bottom and top dmg numbers by 25% or just bump up the top damage number by 50% (either way gets you a 25% boost in average dmg/dps).<br />
<br />
6. Flashfires. Nerfed and less than thrilled with the results, but let's just leave it alone now and focus on improving other spells. No more changes here.<br />
<br />
7. Ball Lightning. I can't see the attraction of this spell. Long cast time, no resist mod, on a highly resistable base, poor dps, and mediocre efficiency. Drop the cast time to 5 seconds and make it mr-100 and keep mana cost where it is now and you bet I would mem and cast this. Otherwise, it's wasted space.<br />
<br />
8. Cold Snap. Same as Flashfires. Let's not mess with this any more.<br />
<br />
9. Lavalure. Ok, here we come to a huge and long-standing problem. The lure spells. These are low efficiency and terrible dps for a very high resist mod. I am a fan of making reasonable trade-offs but given that dps melees almost never have to face these kinds of dps-crushing tradeoffs to do just minimal damage to a mob, there is something horribly out of whack with the lure spells. Ok, so if we need to keep these mana-costly, I understand, but let's really look at improving their dps level by cutting casting time and raising both damage and mana cost. If we up the damage and mana cost both by 50% we can retain their current mana-sucking low efficiency but have some room to play with the cast times to make them viable raid dps. With a 50% bump in damage if you set them to 4 second casting times you actually get some acceptable dps ratings out of these spells. They still become a major tradeoff in both dps and efficiency over many of our other spells, but the lures actually look good for resistant raid mobs if these changes are made.<br />
<br />
10. Cloudburst Strike. The resist mod ought to be -50 instead of -20. Otherwise, same deal as the other instants, let's not mess with this any more.<br />
<br />
11. Leap of Sparks. Straight up, change the resist mod to -100 and increase the damage by 25% and then you have a good short-cast spell with acceptable dps, acceptable efficiency, and a good resist mod.<br />
<br />
12. Rimelure. Same issues as Lavalure and should get the same fixes:  increase damage and mana cost by 50% and reduce the cast time to 4 seconds.<br />
<br />
Ok, so that's what I have for the 71-75 spells. I've skipped some of the more complex spells or ones where I didn't yet have a clear picture on what should be done to improve them. I am sure that lots of other wizards have different ideas or suggestions, but these changes above allow us to increase the reliability, durability, and diversity of the wizard's toolbox for doing damage in groups and in raids but keeps wizards roughly at their current level of dps. In other words, it makes the class more interesting to play and more versatile in dealing their damage while reducing the problems with highly resistant mobs or excessively long fights but does not overpower wizards such that they will be nuking small planets solo.<br />
<br />
I'm very interested in the response from the wizard community and particularly from the devs. I am sending this as a PM and also posting it on the wizard forums.<br />
<br />
Thanks for reading.<br />
<br />
Catamander Zeno<br />
(aka Attropos Zeno)
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
