<tr valign="top">
	<td class="alt2" width="175">
	
	
			<div id="postmenu_1146756">
				
				
				<a class="bigusername" href="member.php?s=004102da16825682bc7ad31383d3761c&amp;u=250">Yakk</a>
				<script type="text/javascript"> vbmenu_register("postmenu_1146756", true); </script>
				
			</div>
			
			<div class="smallfont">Forum Evoker</div>
			
			
			
		




			<div class="smallfont">

<!-- Profiles -->
 
<!-- / Profiles -->



				&nbsp;<br />
				<div>   </div>
			</div>				
	
	
	
	</td>
	
	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1146756">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1146756">
                  
                  *sigh*.<br />
<br />
A spell that does 500 DPS does 500 DPS, regardless of it being a long-casting time spell with medium damage, or a short casting time spell with low damage.<br />
<br />
Longer casting time spells are:<br />
Harder to time, easier to interrupt, and are boosted by spell haste items more.<br />
Their variance in response to resists is higher.  Their special proc abilities are more costly.<br />
<br />
The DPS of a spell can be changed independantly of the casting time of a spell.<br />
<br />
If you want to rework spells this much, try to make it so that each spell has a weakness -- a reason not to use it -- and at least one perk -- a reason to use it.<br />
<br />
...<br />
<br />
In XP groups, it is very effective to &quot;dump and pump&quot;, dump your mana into damage, then pump your mana up via OOC regen.<br />
<br />
How do we make it tempting to use anything other than instant nukes in that situation?  It is really hard to make anything except for &quot;dump your mana ASAP using non-horridly efficient blasts&quot; the ideal strategy.<br />
<br />
...<br />
<br />
In situations where you can't get ahold of OOC regen (raids), you have a relatively known amount of time and known amount of mana to burn on killing the target.  One can presume one also knows the resists levels of the target.<br />
<br />
This isn't that hard to model: the trick is, how can you make it efficient for a wizard to cast more than a handful of nukes in such a situation?  Ideally one would want the raid-nuke game to be easier than &quot;3 1 2 1 2 3 1 2 1 2 3 1 2 1 2 3...&quot;<br />
<br />
Things like concussion recourse, the recourses on instant nukes, the weave buff on mana flare, and GoRM mean that some decisions have to be made during the fight.  Can we push more things like that into the nuking game?<br />
<br />
...<br />
<br />
What about adding more tweaks to spells?<br />
<br />
Low-aggro nukes that contain a concussion-type effect.<br />
Chance-based secondary effects and recourses.<br />
High-aggro nukes with other advantages.<br />
Long recast times on otherwise amazing spells.
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td class="alt2">
		<img class="inlineimg" src="images/legacy_images/statusicon/user_offline.gif" alt="Yakk is offline" border="0" />


		
		
		
